itor-last = Coogan |editor-first = Michael D |title = The Oxford History of the Biblical World |year = 2001 | origyear=1998 |publisher = Oxford University Press | chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=4DVHJRFW3mYC | pages=58\u201389 | ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book |last = Smith | first = Mark S | title = The Early History of God | year = 2002 | publisher = Eerdmans | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=1yM3AuBh4AsC |ref = harv| isbn = 9780802839725 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Sparks | first = Kenton L | title = Ethnicity and Identity in Ancient Israel | year = 1998 | publisher = Eisenbrauns |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=KztVonFGqcsC |ref = harv| isbn = 9781575060330 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Strahan|first1= A|year= 1896|title= The contemporary review|journal= The Contemporary Review|volume= 69|issue= |pages= 624\u201326|doi= |url= https://books.google.com/?id=ojYeAQAAIAAJ |accessdate= 19 Jan 2011|ref = harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1 = Theis |first1 = Christopher |last2= van der Veen | first2= Peter | title = Israel in Canaan. (Long) Before Pharaoh Merenptah? A fresh look at Berlin statue pedestal relief 21687 |journal = Journal of Ancient Egyptian Interconnections |volume=2 |issue=4 |pages=15\u201325 |url = https://www.academia.edu/12078547 |doi=10.2458/azu_jaei_v02i4_van_der_veen|year = 2003 }}\n* {{cite book |last1 = Whitelam |first1 = Keith W |chapter = The Identity of Early Israel: The Realignment and Transformation of Late Bronze-Iron Age Palestine |editor-last = Exum |editor-first = J Cheryl |editor-link = J. Cheryl Exum |title = The Historical Books |year = 1997 |publisher = Continuum | chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7RWmwIgcGfMC |ref = harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title= Encyclopaedia Biblica: A Critical Dictionary of the Literary, Political and Religion History, the Archeology, Geography and Natural History of the Bible |editor1-last=Cheyne|editor1-first=Thomas Kelly | editor1-link=Thomas Kelly Cheyne | editor2-last= Black | editor2-first=J. Sutherland |year= 1899|title-link=Encyclopaedia Biblica}}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Metcalfe|first1= William Musham |last2= Erskine|first2=  Ruaraidh|year= 1897|title= The Scottish review|journal= The Scottish Review|volume= 29|issue= |pages= 125|doi= |url= https://books.google.com/?id=ilEcAQAAIAAJ}}\n* {{cite book |last = Nestor |first = Dermot |title = Ethnicity and Identity in Ancient Israel |year = 2010 | publisher = Continuum |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=LfCC9k2NP2IC |isbn = 9780567012975 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Nibbi|first1= Alessandra|year= 1996|title= Some Remarks on the Merenptah Stela and the So-Called Name of Israel|journal= Discussions in Egyptology, Oxford|volume= 36|issue= |pages= 79\u2013102}}\n* Dever, William G. 1995. \u201cCeramics, Ethnicity, and the Question of Israel\u2019s Origin.\u201d ''The Biblical Archaeologist'' 58: 200\u201313.\n* Frerichs, Ernest S., and Leonard H. Lesko, eds. 1997. ''Exodus: The Egyptian Evidence.'' Winona Lake, IN: Eisenbrauns.\n* Hjelm, Ingrid and Thomas L. Thompson. 2002. \"The Victory Song of Merneptah, Israel and the People of Palestine.\" ''Journal for the Study of the Old Testament'' 27, no. 1: 3\u201318. {{doi|10.1177/030908920202700101}}.\n* Miller, Robert D. 2004. \"Identifying Earliest Israel.\" ''Bulletin of the American Schools of Oriental Research'' no. 333: 55\u201368. {{doi|10.2307/1357794}}.\n* Nestor, Dermot. 2015. \"[https://www.academia.edu/13007853/Merneptahs_Israel_and_the_Absence_of_Origins_in_Biblical_Scholarship Merneptah\u2019s \u2018Israel\u2019 and the Absence of Origins in Biblical Scholarship].\" ''Currents in Biblical Research'' 13, no. 3: 293\u2013329. {{doi|10.1177/1476993X14534792}}. \n* Shanks, Herschel. 2012. \u201cWhen did ancient Israel begin?\u201d ''Biblical Archaeology Review'' 38, no. 1: 59\u201367.\n* Wiener, Malcolm H. 2014. \u201cDating the Emergence of Historical Israel in Light of Recent Developments in Egyptian Chronology.\u201d ''Journal of the Institute of Archaeology of Tel Aviv University'' 41, no. 1: 50\u201354. {{doi|10.1179/0334435514Z.00000000035}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Library resources box |by=no |onlinebooks=yes |others=yes |about=yes |label=Merneptah Stele\n  |viaf= |lccn= |lcheading= |wikititle= }}\n* {{cite web |url= http://prophetess.lstc.edu/~rklein/Doc6/Merneptah.htm|title= The Merneptah Stela|last=Klein | first= Ralph W.|publisher= Lutheran School of Theology at Chicago}}\n* {{cite web| url = http://bibledudes.com/biblical-studies/finds/merneptah-translation.php | type = full translation | first = Miriam | last = Lichtheim | title = Merneptah Stele| publisher = Bible dudes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:13th-century BC steles]]\n[[Category:1896 archaeological discoveries]]\n[[Category:Ancient Egyptian stelas]]\n[[Category:Victory steles]]\n[[Category:Ancient Israel and Judah]]\n[[Category:Ancient Egyptian texts]]\n[[Category:Foreign contacts of ancient Egypt]]\n[[Category:Egyptian Museum]]\n[[Category:Late Bronze Age collapse]]\n", "name_user": "46.19.86.163", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merneptah_Stele"}
{"title_page": "Uta Barth", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Uta Barth\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = <!--only use if different from name-->\n| birth_date       = 1958 <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living artists, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead -->\n| birth_place      = [[Berlin, Germany]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = Germany, United States\n| education        = [[University of California, Davis]];<br> [[University of California, Los Angeles]]\n| known_for        = Photography\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| awards           = [[MacArthur Fellows Program]]\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = {{URL|http://utabarth.net/}}\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n'''Uta Barth''' (born 1958)<ref name=\"Phaidon Editors\">{{cite book |last1=Phaidon Editors |title=Great women artists |date=2019 |publisher=Phaidon Press |isbn=978-0714878775 |page=51}}</ref> is a contemporary German-American whose work addresses themes such as perception, optical illusion and non-place. Her early work emerged in the late 1980s and 1990s, \u201cinverting the notion of background and foreground<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lee, Pamela M.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/52738167|title=Uta Barth|date=2004|publisher=Phaidon|others=Higgs, Matthew., Gilbert-Rolfe, Jeremy.|isbn=0-7148-4153-6|location=London|oclc=52738167}}</ref>\u201d and bringing awareness to a viewer\u2019s attention to visual information with in the photographic frame. Her work is as much about vision and perception as it is about the failure to see, the faith humans place in the mechanics of perception, and the precarious nature of perceptual habits. Barth\u2019s says this about her art practice: \u201cThe question for me always is how can I make you aware of your own looking, instead of losing your attention to thoughts about what it is that you are looking at\u201d (Lee, pg. 36). \n\n\n[[photographer]] who lives and works in [[Los Angeles]], California. Barth is a 2012 [[MacArthur Fellows Program|MacArthur Fellow]]<ref>{{cite web|title=2012 MacArthur Foundation 'Genius Grant' Winners|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/2012-macarthur-foundation-genius-grant-winners#overlay-context=users/rjagodzinski|work=1 October 2012|publisher=AP|accessdate=1 October 2012}}</ref> and a recipient of the [[Guggenheim Fellowship|John Simon Guggenheim Fellowship]] in 2004\u201105.<ref>http://www.gf.org/fellows/826-uta-barth {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110117045917/http://www.gf.org/fellows/826-uta-barth |date=2011-01-17 }} Guggenheim Foundation 2004 Fellows Page accessed 2010-01-15</ref>\n\n==Education and teaching==\nBarth was born in [[Berlin]], [[Germany]] in 1958. She received a bachelor of arts degree from the [[University of California, Davis]] and a [[Master of Fine Arts]] from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].\nFrom 1990 to 2008, she was a professor in the Art Department of the [[University of California, Riverside]], where she is currently a professor of art emeritus. After receiving the MacArthur Fellowship in October 2012, she noted that she still plans to teach on a part-time basis because teaching forces her to \"put language to\" what she is thinking.<ref name=UCR>{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Bettye|title=Art Professor Wins MacArthur Fellowship|url=http://ucrtoday.ucr.edu/9173|accessdate=2 October 2012|newspaper=UCR Today|date=1 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\nBarth's work is represented in numerous public and private collections worldwide, including the [[Museum of Modern Art]], the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], and the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] in [[New York City|New York]]; the [[Tate Gallery]] in [[London]]; the [[Art Institute of Chicago]] and the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago|Museum of Contemporary Art]] in [[Chicago]]; and the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles|Museum of Contemporary Art]], the [[J.&nbsp;Paul Getty Museum]], and the [[Hammer Museum]] in Los Angeles; the [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]]; the [[Walker Art Center]] in [[Minneapolis]]; and [[Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art]] in [[North Adams, Massachusetts|North Adams]], Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Uta Barth|url=http://www.grmandco.com/books/7/23/37|publisher=Gregory R. Miller & Co.|accessdate=2 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nHer work is exhibited regularly and has been shown in one-person and group exhibitions in galleries and museums throughout the United States and Europe, including [[New York City|New York]], Los Angeles, [[San Francisco]], London, [[Stockholm]], Sweden, [[D\u00fcsseldorf]], Germany, [[Bilbao]], Spain, and [[Tokyo]], Japan.<ref name=UCR />\n\nHer recent work includes [http://www.tilted-arc.com/2015/01/27/artists-on-rhythm-uta-barth/nggallery/thumbnails Artists of Rhythm] and the following excerpt describes the exhibit:\n\n\"We asked Uta Barth, an artist that has focused on what we experience in the periphery, moments that pass without particular attention, to comment on the role of rhythm in her photographs. Her work, and how she presents the photographs, reference the subtle unperceived rhythms that live in the subconscious.\" ([http://www.tilted-arc.com/2015/01/27/artists-on-rhythm-uta-barth/nggallery/thumbnails Henken, Laura])\n\nIn relation to her ''Field'' and ''Ground'' series, which depict blurred and empty foregrounds, Barth has stated: \"I am interested in the conventions of picture-making, in the desire to picture the world and in our relationship, our continual love for and fascination with pictures.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Uta Barth: in between places|last=Barth|first=Uta|last2=Conkelton|first2=Sheryl|last3=Ferguson|first3=Russell|last4=Martin|first4=Timothy|last5=Henry Art Gallery|date=2000-01-01|publisher=Henry Art Gallery, University of Washington|isbn=0935558373|location=Seattle, Wash.|oclc = 45567870|language=English}}</ref>\n\n== Monographs ==\n* 2012 - Uta Barth. ... to draw with light. Blind Spot, New York.\n* 2010 - Uta Barth: The Long Now. Greg R. Miller & Co., New York. Essays by Jonathan Crary, Russell Ferguson, and Holly Myers.\n* 2006 - Uta Barth 2006: Just Spanning Time. Essay by Cheryl Kaplan Exh. cat. Minneapolis: Franklin Art Works. \n* 2004 - Uta Barth: ''white blind'' (bright red). Santa Fe: SITE Santa Fe. Essay by Jan Tumlir.\n* 2004 - Uta Barth. London: Phaidon Press. Essays by Uta Barth, Pamela Lee, and Jeremy Gilbert-Rolfe; interview with Matthew Higgs; and selected writings by [[Joan Didion]].\n* 2000 - Uta Barth: ... and of time. Artist's book. Essay by Timothy Martin. Published in conjunction with a project commissioned by the [[J.&nbsp;Paul Getty Museum]], Los Angeles, for the exhibition \"Departures: 11&nbsp;Artists\".\n* 2000 - At the Edge of the Decipherable: Recent Photographs by Uta Barth. 2nd ed. Essay by [[Elizabeth A.&nbsp;T. Smith]]. Los Angeles: The Museum of Contemporary Art and St.&nbsp;Ann's Press.\n* 2000 - Uta Barth: In Between Places. Seattle: Henry Art Gallery and University of Washington. Essays by Sheryl Conkelton, Russell Ferguson, and Timothy Martin.\n* 1999 - Uta Barth: nowhere near. Artist's book. Essay by Jan Tumlir. Published in conjunction with a three-part exhibition project by the same name at ACME., Los Angeles; Bonakdar Jancou Gallery, New York; and Andr\u00e9hn-Schiptjenko, Stockholm.\n* 1999 - Uta Barth: nowhere near. Exh. brochure. Overland Park, Kansas: Johnson County Community College Art Gallery. Text by Jan Tumlir.\n* 1995 - At the Edge of the Decipherable: Recent Photographs by Uta Barth. Essay by Elizabeth A.&nbsp;T. Smith. Los Angeles: The Museum of Contemporary Art.\n\n== Selected grants and fellowships ==\n* '''2012'''            [[MacArthur Fellows Program|MacArthur Fellowship]]\n* '''2012'''  Anonymous Was A Woman Award\n* '''2010'''  Nominated for the 2011 [[Deutsche B\u00f6rse Photography Prize]]\n* '''2007'''  [[Eli Broad#Philanthropy|Broad Art Foundation]] USA Artist Fellowship\n* '''2004\u201305'''         John Simon Guggenheim Fellowship\n* '''1996'''  Nominated Tiffany Award\n* '''1994\u201395'''         [[National Endowment for the Arts]] Visual Artist Fellowship\n* '''1995'''  AMI Grant (Art Matters Inc., New York), Visual Artist Fellowship\n* '''1992\u201393'''         AMI Grant (Art Matters Inc., New York), Visual Artist Fellowship\n* '''1990\u201391'''         National Endowment for the Arts, Visual Artist Fellowship\n* '''1983\u201384'''         National Arts Association<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tanyabonakdargallery.com/artists/uta-barth/series-photography |title=Tanya Bonakdar Gallery artists page; Tanya Bonakdar Gallery (New York). |accessdate=2011-01-30}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of German women artists]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.utabarth.net/}}\n* [http://www.tanyabonakdargallery.com/artists/uta-barth/series-photography Uta Barth - Tanya Bonakdar Gallery]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170407054618/http://1301pe.com/artists/images.asp?aid=22 Uta Barth - 1301PE Gallery, Los Angeles]\n* [http://utabarth.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/resume.pdf Full official resume]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barth, Uta}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:MacArthur Fellows]]\n[[Category:German women photographers]]\n[[Category:Women photographers]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:German contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:University of California, Davis alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Uta Barth\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = <!--only use if different from name-->\n| birth_date       = 1958 <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living artists, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead -->\n| birth_place      = [[Berlin, Germany]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = Germany, United States\n| education        = [[University of California, Davis]];<br> [[University of California, Los Angeles]]\n| known_for        = Photography\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| awards           = [[MacArthur Fellows Program]]\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = {{URL|http://utabarth.net/}}\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n'''Uta Barth''' (born 1958)<ref name=\"Phaidon Editors\">{{cite book |last1=Phaidon Editors |title=Great women artists |date=2019 |publisher=Phaidon Press |isbn=978-0714878775 |page=51}}</ref> is a contemporary [[photographer]] who lives and works in [[Los Angeles]], California. Barth is a 2012 [[MacArthur Fellows Program|MacArthur Fellow]]<ref>{{cite web|title=2012 MacArthur Foundation 'Genius Grant' Winners|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/2012-macarthur-foundation-genius-grant-winners#overlay-context=users/rjagodzinski|work=1 October 2012|publisher=AP|accessdate=1 October 2012}}</ref> and a recipient of the [[Guggenheim Fellowship|John Simon Guggenheim Fellowship]] in 2004\u201105.<ref>http://www.gf.org/fellows/826-uta-barth {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110117045917/http://www.gf.org/fellows/826-uta-barth |date=2011-01-17 }} Guggenheim Foundation 2004 Fellows Page accessed 2010-01-15</ref>\n\n==Education and teaching==\nBarth was born in [[Berlin]], [[Germany]] in 1958. She received a bachelor of arts degree from the [[University of California, Davis]] and a [[Master of Fine Arts]] from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].\nFrom 1990 to 2008, she was a professor in the Art Department of the [[University of California, Riverside]], where she is currently a professor of art emeritus. After receiving the MacArthur Fellowship in October 2012, she noted that she still plans to teach on a part-time basis because teaching forces her to \"put language to\" what she is thinking.<ref name=UCR>{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Bettye|title=Art Professor Wins MacArthur Fellowship|url=http://ucrtoday.ucr.edu/9173|accessdate=2 October 2012|newspaper=UCR Today|date=1 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Collections==\nBarth's work is represented in numerous public and private collections worldwide, including the [[Museum of Modern Art]], the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], and the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] in [[New York City|New York]]; the [[Tate Gallery]] in [[London]]; the [[Art Institute of Chicago]] and the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago|Museum of Contemporary Art]] in [[Chicago]]; and the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles|Museum of Contemporary Art]], the [[J.&nbsp;Paul Getty Museum]], and the [[Hammer Museum]] in Los Angeles; the [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]]; the [[Walker Art Center]] in [[Minneapolis]]; and [[Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art]] in [[North Adams, Massachusetts|North Adams]], Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Uta Barth|url=http://www.grmandco.com/books/7/23/37|publisher=Gregory R. Miller & Co.|accessdate=2 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nHer work is exhibited regularly and has been shown in one-person and group exhibitions in galleries and museums throughout the United States and Europe, including [[New York City|New York]], Los Angeles, [[San Francisco]], London, [[Stockholm]], Sweden, [[D\u00fcsseldorf]], Germany, [[Bilbao]], Spain, and [[Tokyo]], Japan.<ref name=UCR />\n\nHer recent work includes [http://www.tilted-arc.com/2015/01/27/artists-on-rhythm-uta-barth/nggallery/thumbnails Artists of Rhythm] and the following excerpt describes the exhibit:\n\n\"We asked Uta Barth, an artist that has focused on what we experience in the periphery, moments that pass without particular attention, to comment on the role of rhythm in her photographs. Her work, and how she presents the photographs, reference the subtle unperceived rhythms that live in the subconscious.\" ([http://www.tilted-arc.com/2015/01/27/artists-on-rhythm-uta-barth/nggallery/thumbnails Henken, Laura])\n\nIn relation to her ''Field'' and ''Ground'' series, which depict blurred and empty foregrounds, Barth has stated: \"I am interested in the conventions of picture-making, in the desire to picture the world and in our relationship, our continual love for and fascination with pictures.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Uta Barth: in between places|last=Barth|first=Uta|last2=Conkelton|first2=Sheryl|last3=Ferguson|first3=Russell|last4=Martin|first4=Timothy|last5=Henry Art Gallery|date=2000-01-01|publisher=Henry Art Gallery, University of Washington|isbn=0935558373|location=Seattle, Wash.|oclc = 45567870|language=English}}</ref>\n\n== Monographs ==\n* 2012 - Uta Barth. ... to draw with light. Blind Spot, New York.\n* 2010 - Uta Barth: The Long Now. Greg R. Miller & Co., New York. Essays by Jonathan Crary, Russell Ferguson, and Holly Myers.\n* 2006 - Uta Barth 2006: Just Spanning Time. Essay by Cheryl Kaplan Exh. cat. Minneapolis: Franklin Art Works. \n* 2004 - Uta Barth: ''white blind'' (bright red). Santa Fe: SITE Santa Fe. Essay by Jan Tumlir.\n* 2004 - Uta Barth. London: Phaidon Press. Essays by Uta Barth, Pamela Lee, and Jeremy Gilbert-Rolfe; interview with Matthew Higgs; and selected writings by [[Joan Didion]].\n* 2000 - Uta Barth: ... and of time. Artist's book. Essay by Timothy Martin. Published in conjunction with a project commissioned by the [[J.&nbsp;Paul Getty Museum]], Los Angeles, for the exhibition \"Departures: 11&nbsp;Artists\".\n* 2000 - At the Edge of the Decipherable: Recent Photographs by Uta Barth. 2nd ed. Essay by [[Elizabeth A.&nbsp;T. Smith]]. Los Angeles: The Museum of Contemporary Art and St.&nbsp;Ann's Press.\n* 2000 - Uta Barth: In Between Places. Seattle: Henry Art Gallery and University of Washington. Essays by Sheryl Conkelton, Russell Ferguson, and Timothy Martin.\n* 1999 - Uta Barth: nowhere near. Artist's book. Essay by Jan Tumlir. Published in conjunction with a three-part exhibition project by the same name at ACME., Los Angeles; Bonakdar Jancou Gallery, New York; and Andr\u00e9hn-Schiptjenko, Stockholm.\n* 1999 - Uta Barth: nowhere near. Exh. brochure. Overland Park, Kansas: Johnson County Community College Art Gallery. Text by Jan Tumlir.\n* 1995 - At the Edge of the Decipherable: Recent Photographs by Uta Barth. Essay by Elizabeth A.&nbsp;T. Smith. Los Angeles: The Museum of Contemporary Art.\n\n== Selected grants and fellowships ==\n* '''2012'''            [[MacArthur Fellows Program|MacArthur Fellowship]]\n* '''2012'''  Anonymous Was A Woman Award\n* '''2010'''  Nominated for the 2011 [[Deutsche B\u00f6rse Photography Prize]]\n* '''2007'''  [[Eli Broad#Philanthropy|Broad Art Foundation]] USA Artist Fellowship\n* '''2004\u201305'''         John Simon Guggenheim Fellowship\n* '''1996'''  Nominated Tiffany Award\n* '''1994\u201395'''         [[National Endowment for the Arts]] Visual Artist Fellowship\n* '''1995'''  AMI Grant (Art Matters Inc., New York), Visual Artist Fellowship\n* '''1992\u201393'''         AMI Grant (Art Matters Inc., New York), Visual Artist Fellowship\n* '''1990\u201391'''         National Endowment for the Arts, Visual Artist Fellowship\n* '''1983\