{"title_page": "Thomas Medlycott (1662\u20131738)", "text_new": "'''Thomas Medlycott''' (1662\u20131738), of Binfield, Berkshire, and Dublin, Ireland, was a British lawyer who was an Irish attorney general and later Commissioner of Revenue and Excise for Ireland. He was first a Tory and later a Whig politician who sat in the [[Parliament of Ireland]] from 1692 to 1738, and in the [[English House of Commons]] and [[British House of Commons ]] between 1705 and 1734.\n\n==Early life==\nMedlycott was baptized on 22 May 1662, the third son of [[Thomas Medlycott (died 1716)|Thomas Medlycott]] of Abingdon, Berkshire. He was admitted at [[Middle Temple]] in 1680 and was called to the bar in 1687. He married by licence dated 1 January 1687, Sarah Goddard, daughter of Mrs Ursula Goddard, widow, of Mugwell (Monkwell) Street, Cripplegate, London.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/medlycott-thomas-1662-1738 | title= MEDLYCOTT, Thomas (1662-1738), of Binfield, Berks. and Dublin, Ireland | publisher= History of Parliament Online (1690-1715)| accessdate = 21 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Career in Ireland==\nMedlycott began his career in Ireland as secretary and estate manager to [[James Butler, 2nd Duke of Ormonde]]. He was called to the Irish bar 1691 and appointed Attorney-general for the [[County palatine]] of [[County Tipperary|Tipperary]] by 1692. In 1692 he was returned as Irish Member of Parliament for [[Kildare Borough (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Kildare Borough]]  and became Freeman of Drogheda on 1694. He was returned again for Kildare in 1695. In 1697, he was entrusted with a sensitive task of organizing opposition to a bill confirming the King's grant of James II's Irish estates. King William had overridden the former King's settlement of estates, worth about \u00a322,000, on his children and had given them to [[Elizabeth Hamilton, Countess of Orkney|Elizabeth Villiers]], allegedly William III's mistress, which had particularly upset [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Princess Anne]]. Medlycott obtained lands in Kilkenny, Tipperary and Waterford from the Duke of Ormonde in 1698 and 1699 and in 1701 purchased more land in Mayo from Ormond's brother, Lord Arran. In 1703 he was returned as Irish MP for [[Clonmel (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Clonmell]]  and in 1713 for [[Ballynakill (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Ballynakill]].<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==Career in Westminster==\nBy 1705 Medlycott's brother [[James Medlycott|James]] had increased his electoral influence at [[Milborne Port (UK Parliament constituency)|Milborne Port]]  by acquiring additional burgages. At the [[1705 English general election]], Medlycott stood for the borough where his return was virtually guaranteed. During the election campaign the post of deputy-steward of Westminster became available and he immediately wrote to Ormond, the high steward, reminding him that he had previously promised him this office. The Duke kept his word and also obtained a commission in the Irish guards for Medlycott's son. Medlycott was returned in a contest as [[Member of Parliament]] for Milborne Port on his family's interest. In Parliament he voted with the Whigs and the moderate Tories on 25 October 1705 in favour of the Court candidate for Speaker, but in February 1706 he supported the Tories in a disputed election case. He was an assiduous member particularly with regard to Westminster matters. He was involved in three private bills, but his main concern was a bill for the prevention of fires.  At the [[1708 British general election]]  he was returned as MP for Milborne Port and also for [[Westminster (UK Parliament constituency)|Westminster]] where he chose to sit once a petition against his return had been decided in his favour. He continued working hard, particularly with regard to urban matters.  Measures he was involved in included tightening the provisions of his Fires Act, establishing a workhouse in St. Martin-in-the-Fields,  extending the powers of London's commissioners of sewers, regulating hackney coaches, incorporating peruke-makers into the Company of Barbers and Surgeons, raising the militia and limiting long periods of public mourning because of the disastrous effects on the silk trade. He initiated a private estate bill on behalf of the Irish peer Viscount Gormanston and two other estate bills.  In 1710, he followed the Tory line in voting against the impeachment of [[Henry Sacheverell|Dr Sacheverell]].<ref name=HOP/>\n \nMedlycott was returned in a contest at the [[1710 British general election]] and was listed as a \u2018Tory patriot\u2019 who voted for peace during the course of 1711, and as a \u2018worthy patriot\u2019 who assisted in detecting the mismanagements of the former administration. He was also a member of the October Club.. He became a bencher of his Inn in 1712 and in July 1712 was appointed Commissioner of Revenue and Excise for Ireland by Robert Harley Lord Treasurer. He was returned unopposed at the [[1713 British general election]] by which time he was described as a Tory who sometimes voted with the Whig. He spoke in favour of the motion condemning Richard Steele's* published attacks on the ministry on 18 March 1714, but was aligned with the [[Hanoverian Tories]] and spoke on the Court side in the debate on the succession and on 22 April in support of the address of thanks for the peace. He became Chairman of the Committee of elections and privileges in 1714. In July he petitioned Lord Oxford for repayment of the expenses he had incurred back in 1697 carrying out the Queen's commands with regard to her father's former Irish estates when she was princess. However, Anne's death a fortnight later pre-empted any chance of reimbursement. He retained his Irish post as Commissioner for Revenue and Excise after joining the Whigs.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==Later career==\nMedlycott did not stand at the [[1715 British general election]] but was returned as Irish MP for [[Downpatrick (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Downpatrick]]. He remained in Ireland occupied with his official duties and his private affairs. He lost his Irish post in July 1727 but was returned as MP for Milborne Port at the [[1727 British general election]]. He was also returned for the Parliament of Ireland seat at [[Newtown Limavady (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Newtown Limvady]] in 1727. He was reinstated as Commissioner for revenue and excise for Ireland in February 1728 and held it until October 1733 when his son-in-law was appointed his successor, on the ground that Medlycott was \u2018obliged to remain in England as a Member of Parliament\u2019.  In the House he voted with the Government for the excise bill and against the repeal of the Septennial Act. His only recorded speech was made on 21 February 1733 against the clause in a bill relating to the restrictive import of sugar, molasses and rum into Ireland.  He was defeated at Milborne Port at the [[1734 British general election]]  by his nephew, [[Thomas Medlycott (died 1763)|Thomas Medlycott ]]<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/medlycott-thomas-1662-1738 | title= MEDLYCOTT, Thomas (1662-1738), of Binfield, Berks. and Dublin. | publisher= History of Parliament Online (1715-1754)| accessdate = 21 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nMedlycott died before September 1738, leaving two sons and a daughter by his wife Sarah. However he left most of his estate in trust for Thomas John Medlycott, apparently an illegitimate son.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ie}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Francis Leigh (MP for Kildare)|Francis Leigh]] \n| before2= [[Robert Porter (Kildare politician)|Robert Porter]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Kildare Borough (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Kildare Borough]] \n | with = [[Francis Robartes]] 1692\u20131695 \n | with2 =[[William Palmer (Irish politician)|William Palmer]]   1696 \n | with3 = [[John Davys (died 1743)|John Davys]] 1695\u20131703\n| years  = 1715\u20131725 }}\n{{s-aft\n| after  =[[Thomas Jones (Irish politician)|Thomas Jones]]\n | after2= [[Richard Locke (Irish MP)|Richard Locke]]\n}}\n\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Clonmel (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Clonmel]] \n | with = [[Robert Hamerton (politician)|Robert Hamerton]]\n | years  =  1703\u20131713 \n | before = [[Robert Blennerhassett (1652\u20131712)|Robert Blennerhassett]]<br/>[[Richard Moore (died 1699)|Richard Moore]]\n | after  = [[Stephen Moore (1689\u20131750)|Stephen Moore]] <br/> [[Robert Hamerton (politician)|Robert Hamerton]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Ballynakill (Parliament of Ireland constituency)| Ballynakill]] \n | with = [[John Barrington (Irish politician)|John Barrington]]\n | years  = 1713\u20131715 \n | before =[[John Barrington (Irish politician)|John Barrington]]<br/> [[Sir Arthur Gore, 2nd Baronet|Sir Arthur Gore, 2nd Bt]]\n | after  = [[Samuel Freeman (Irish politician)|Samuel Freeman]]  <br/> [[John Weaver (politician)|John Weaver]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Downpatrick (Parliament of Ireland constituency)| Downpatrick]] \n | with = [[Sir Emanuel Moore, 3rd Baronet|Sir Emanuel Moore, 3rd Bt]]\n | years  =  1715\u20131738 \n | before = [[Mathew Forde (1675\u20131729)|Mathew Forde]]<br/> [[Francis Annesley (politician)|Francis Annesley]]\n | after  = [[Edward Southwell (1705\u20131755)|Edward Southwell]]<br/> [[Cromwell Price]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Newtown Limavady (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Newtown Limavady]] \n | with = [[Isaac Manley]] <br> [[Alexander Nesbitt]] 1736\n | years  =  1727\u20131713 \n | before = [[Isaac Manley]] <br/> [[Thomas Marlay]]\n | after  =   [[Alexander Nesbitt]]  <br/> [[Edward Riggs (politician)|Edward Riggs]]\n}}{{s-par|en}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Thomas Travell|Sir Thomas Travell]]\n | before2 = [[John Hunt (died 1721)|John Hunt]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Milborne Port (UK Parliament constituency)|Milborne Port]]\n | years =   [[1705 English general election|1705]]\u2013[[1708 British general election|1708]]\n | with  = [[Thomas Travell|Sir Thomas Travell]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Thomas Travell|Sir Thomas Travell]]\n | after2 = [[Thomas Smith (died 1728)|Thomas Smith]]\n}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Henry Boyle, 1st Baron Carleton|Henry Boyle]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Henry Colt, 1st Baronet|Henry Colt]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Westminster (UK Parliament constituency)|Westminster]]\n | years =   [[1708 British general election|1708]]\u2013[[1715 British general election|1715]]\n | with  = [[Henry Boyle, 1st Baron Carleton|Henry Boyle]] 1708-1710\n | with2 = [[Sir Thomas Crosse, 1st Baronet|Thomas Crosse]] 1710-1715\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir Thomas Crosse, 1st Baronet|Thomas Crosse]]\n | after2 = [[Edward Wortley Montagu (diplomat)|Edward Wortley Montagu]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Michael Harvey (died 1748)|Michael Harvey]]\n | before2 = [[George Speke (died 1753)|George Speke]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Milborne Port (UK Parliament constituency)|Milborne Port]]\n | years =   [[1727 British general election|1727]]\u2013[[1734 British general election|1734]]\n | with  = [[Michael Harvey (died 1748)|Michael Harvey]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Michael Harvey (died 1748)|Michael Harvey]]\n | after2 = [[Thomas Medlycott (died 1763)|Thomas Medlycott, junior]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Medlycott, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1662 births]]\n[[Category:1738 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1708\u20131710]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1710\u20131713]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1713\u20131715]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n", "text_old": "'''Thomas Medlycott''' (1662\u20131738), of Binfield, Berkshire, and Dublin, Ireland, was a British lawyer who was an Irish attorney general and later Commissioner of Revenue and Excise for Ireland. He was first a Tory and later a Whig politician who sat in the [[Parliament of Ireland]] from 1692 to 1738, and in the [[English House of Commons]] and [[British House of Commons ]] between 1705 and 1734.\n\n==Early life==\nMedlycott was baptized on 22 May 1662, the third son of [[Thomas Medlycott (died 1716)|Thomas Medlycott]] of Abingdon, Berkshire. He was admitted at [[Middle Temple]] in 1680 and was called to the bar in 1687. He married by licence dated 1 January 1687, Sarah Goddard, daughter of Mrs Ursula Goddard, widow, of Mugwell (Monkwell) Street, Cripplegate, London.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/medlycott-thomas-1662-1738 | title= MEDLYCOTT, Thomas (1662-1738), of Binfield, Berks. and Dublin, Ireland | publisher= History of Parliament Online (1690-1715)| accessdate = 21 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Career in Ireland==\nMedlycott began his career in Ireland as secretary and estate manager to [[James Butler, 2nd Duke of Ormonde]]. He was called to the Irish bar 1691 and appointed Attorney-general for the [[County palatine]] of [[County Tipperary|Tipperary]] by 1692. In 1692 he was returned as Irish Member of Parliament for [[Kildare Borough (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Kildare Borough]]  and became Freeman of Drogheda on 1694. He was returned again for Kildare in 1695. In 1697, he was entrusted with a sensitive task of organizing opposition to a bill confirming the King\u2019s grant of James II\u2019s Irish estates. King William had overridden the former King\u2019s settlement of estates, worth about \u00a322,000, on his children and had given them to [[Elizabeth Hamilton, Countess of Orkney|Elizabeth Villiers]], allegedly William III\u2019s mistress, which had particularly upset [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Princess Anne]]. Medlycott obtained lands in Kilkenny, Tipperary and Waterford from the Duke of Ormonde in 1698 and 1699 and in 1701 purchased more land in Mayo from Ormond\u2019s brother, Lord Arran. In 1703 he was returned as Irish MP for [[Clonmel (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Clonmell]]  and in 1713 for [[Ballynakill (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Ballynakill]].<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==Career in Westminster==\nBy 1705 Medlycott\u2019s brother [[James Medlycott|James]] had increased his electoral influence at [[Milborne Port (UK Parliament constituency)|Milborne Port]]  by acquiring additional burgages. At the [[1705 English general election]], Medlycott stood for the borough where his return was virtually guaranteed. During the election campaign the post of deputy-steward of Westminster became available and he immediately wrote to Ormond, the high steward, reminding him that he had previously promised him this office. The Duke kept his word and also obtained a commission in the Irish guards for Medlycott\u2019s son. Medlycott was returned in a contest as [[Member of Parliament]] for Milborne Port on his family\u2019s interest. In Parliament he voted with the Whigs and the moderate Tories on 25 October 1705 in favour of the Court candidate for Speaker, but in February 1706 he supported the Tories in a disputed election case. He was an assiduous member particularly with regard to Westminster matters. He was involved in three private bills, but his main concern was a bill for the prevention of fires.  At the [[1708 British general election]]  he was returned as MP for Milborne Port and also for [[Westminster (UK Parliament constituency)|Westminster]] where he chose to sit once a petition against his return had been decided in his favour. He continued working hard, particularly with regard to urban matters.  Measures he was involved in included tightening the provisions of his Fires Act, establishing a workhouse in St. Martin-in-the-Fields,  extending the powers of London\u2019s commissioners of sewers, regulating hackney coaches, incorporating peruke-makers into the Company of Barbers and Surgeons, raising the militia and limiting long periods of public mourning because of the disastrous effects on the silk trade. He initiated a private estate bill on behalf of the Irish peer Viscount Gormanston and two other estate bills.  In 1710, he followed the Tory line in voting against the impeachment of [[Henry Sacheverell|Dr Sacheverell]].<ref name=HOP/>\n \nMedlycott was returned in a contest at the [[1710 British general election]] and was listed as a \u2018Tory patriot\u2019 who voted for peace during the course of 1711, and as a \u2018worthy patriot\u2019 who assisted in detecting the mismanagements of the former administration. He was also a member of the October Club.. He became a bencher of his Inn in 1712 and in July 1712 was appointed Commissioner of Revenue and Excise for Ireland by Robert Harley Lord Treasurer. He was returned unopposed at the [[1713 British general election]] by which time he was described as a Tory who sometimes voted with the Whig. He spoke in favour of the motion condemning Richard Steele\u2019s* published attacks on the ministry on 18 March 1714, but was aligned with the [[Hanoverian Tories]] and spoke on the Court side in the debate on the succession and on 22 April in support of the address of thanks for the peace. He became Chairman of the Committee of elections and privileges in 1714. In July he petitioned Lord Oxford for repayment of the expenses he had incurred back in 1697 carrying out the Queen\u2019s commands with regard to her father\u2019s former Irish estates when she was princess. However, Anne\u2019s death a fortnight later pre-empted any chance of reimbursement. He retained his Irish post as Commissioner for Revenue and Excise after joining the Whigs.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==Later career==\nMedlycott did not stand at the [[1715 British general election]] but was returned as Irish MP for [[Downpatrick (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Downpatrick]]. He remained in Ireland occupied with his official duties and his private affairs. He lost his Irish post in July 1727 but was returned as MP for Milborne Port at the [[1727 British general election]]. He was also returned for the Parliament of Ireland seat at [[Newtown Limavady (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Newtown Limvady]] in 1727. He was reinstated as Commissioner for revenue and excise for Ireland in February 1728 and held it until October 1733 when his son-in-law was appointed his successor, on the ground that Medlycott was \u2018obliged to remain in England as a Member of Parliament\u2019.  In the House he voted with the Government for the excise bill and against the repeal of the Septennial Act. His only recorded speech was made on 21 February 1733 against the clause in a bill relating to the restrictive import of sugar, molasses and rum into Ireland.  He was defeated at Milborne Port at the [[1734 British general election]]  by his nephew, [[Thomas Medlycott (died 1763)|Thomas Medlycott ]]<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/medlycott-thomas-1662-1738 | title= MEDLYCOTT, Thomas (1662-1738), of Binfield, Berks. and Dublin. | publisher= History of Parliament Online (1715-1754)| accessdate = 21 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nMedlycott died before September 1738, leaving two sons and a daughter by his wife Sarah. However he left most of his estate in trust for Thomas John Medlycott, apparently an illegitimate son.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ie}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Francis Leigh (MP for Kildare)|Francis Leigh]] \n| before2= [[Robert Porter (Kildare politician)|Robert Porter]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Kildare Borough (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Kildare Borough]] \n | with = [[Francis Robartes]] 1692\u20131695 \n | with2 =[[William Palmer (Irish politician)|William Palmer]]   1696 \n | with3 = [[John Davys (died 1743)|John Davys]] 1695\u20131703\n| years  = 1715\u20131725 }}\n{{s-aft\n| after  =[[Thomas Jones (Irish politician)|Thomas Jones]]\n | after2= [[Richard Locke (Irish MP)|Richard Locke]]\n}}\n\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Clonmel (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Clonmel]] \n | with = [[Robert Hamerton (politician)|Robert Hamerton]]\n | years  =  1703\u20131713 \n | before = [[Robert Blennerhassett (1652\u20131712)|Robert Blennerhassett]]<br/>[[Richard Moore (died 1699)|Richard Moore]]\n | after  = [[Stephen Moore (1689\u20131750)|Stephen Moore]] <br/> [[Robert Hamerton (politician)|Robert Hamerton]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Ballynakill (Parliament of Ireland constituency)| Ballynakill]] \n | with = [[John Barrington (Irish politician)|John Barrington]]\n | years  = 1713\u20131715 \n | before =[[John Barrington (Irish politician)|John Barrington]]<br/> [[Sir Arthur Gore, 2nd Baronet|Sir Arthur Gore, 2nd Bt]]\n | after  = [[Samuel Freeman (Irish politician)|Samuel Freeman]]  <br/> [[John Weaver (politician)|John Weaver]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Downpatrick (Parliament of Ireland constituency)| Downpatrick]] \n | with = [[Sir Emanuel Moore, 3rd Baronet|Sir Emanuel Moore, 3rd Bt]]\n | years  =  1715\u20131738 \n | before = [[Mathew Forde (1675\u20131729)|Mathew Forde]]<br/> [[Francis Annesley (politician)|Francis Annesley]]\n | after  = [[Edward Southwell (1705\u20131755)|Edward Southwell]]<br/> [[Cromwell Price]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Newtown Limavady (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Newtown Limavady]] \n | with = [[Isaac Manley]] <br> [[Alexander Nesbitt]] 1736\n | years  =  1727\u20131713 \n | before